block post-content
    p.post-container__text-block In an age where information is readily accessible with just a few clicks, individuals are increasingly turning to the internet for medical information and self-diagnosis. The article&nbsp;
                a(href='https://www.healthaffairs.org/content/forefront/seeking-diagnosis-internet') “Seeking Diagnosis on the Internet”&nbsp;
                | published in Health Affairs explores this growing trend and delves into the need for healthcare organizations to provide credible, accessible education.

    p.post-container__text-block The internet has become a vast repository of medical information, providing people with an abundance of resources to better understand their symptoms and potential health conditions. However, unguided internet research poses significant challenges:

    p.post-container__text-block
        ul
            li
                u Misinformation and Misdiagnosis:
                span &nbsp;The internet is rife with misinformation, and relying solely on online sources can lead to incorrect self-diagnoses or unwarranted panic.
            li
                u Overlooking Professional Medical Advice:
                span &nbsp;While online information can be informative, it should not replace the expertise of healthcare professionals. Relying solely on digital sources might lead to delays in seeking proper medical care.
            li
                u Heightened Anxiety:
                span &nbsp;Reading about a wide range of possible conditions online might escalate anxiety levels, as users may become convinced that they have a serious ailment.
            li
                u Confirmation Bias:
                span &nbsp;People tend to focus on information that confirms their suspicions, potentially leading them down a path of misguided self-diagnosis.

    p.post-container__text-block Healthcare providers typically bear the brunt of these challenges. They spend precious time answering irrelevant questions, consoling panicked patients, and attempting to reverse the damage of misinformation.

    p.post-container__text-block In order to ensure patients are appropriately educated about their conditions, providers can implement digital health technologies, such as Diya Health, to provide the right information at the right time. Improving access to trusted, reliable education has multiple benefits:

    p.post-container__text-block
        ul
            li
                u Patient Empowerment
                span &nbsp;Patients take an active role in their health by learning about their condition and treatment options. This can empower patients to make informed decisions about their care.
            li
                u Ease of Access:
                span &nbsp;Active education delivery allows for quick retrieval of relevant information, helping patients find quick answers to their questions.
            li
                u Effective Use of Provider Time:
                span &nbsp;With access to personalized, trusted education, patients are better prepared for the next steps in their care. This leads to more meaningful and effective provider-patient conversations.
    p.post-container__text-block In conclusion, the internet has undoubtedly transformed the way patients seek medical information and diagnoses. However, the pitfalls of misinformation and the potential to undermine professional medical advice must not be overlooked. The key lies in leveraging the digital health platforms as a tool to enhance health literacy and facilitate productive conversations with healthcare providers.
    p.post-container__text-block
        strong Reference:
        ul
            li "Seeking Diagnosis On The Internet", Health Affairs Forefront, August 28, 2023. DOI: 10.1377/forefront.20230824.629654
